  <para>
    <link linkend='MenuItem-OOF.Skeleton.PinNodes'>Pin</link> internal
    boundary nodes.  Internal boundary nodes are those that are along
    the boundaries of regions of different <link
    linkend='Section-Concepts-PixelCategory'>pixel categories</link>
    in the &micro;.
  </para>
  <para>
    Pinning internal boundaries is especially useful to clean up a
    &skel; after it has adapted to the material boundaries of a
    &micro;.  <xref linkend="Figure-pininternal"/> shows a &skel; with
    pinned internal boundary nodes.  <xref
    linkend="Figure-pinsmooth"/> shows the same &skel; after having
    been <link linkend="RegisteredClass-Smooth">smoothed</link>.  The
    pinned nodes have not moved, although the
    <varname>targets</varname> parameter for <xref
    linkend="RegisteredClass-Smooth"/> was set to <xref
    linkend="RegisteredClass-AllNodes"/>.

  </para>
  <figure id="Figure-pininternal">
    <title>Pinning Internal Boundary Nodes</title>
    <mediaobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/pinnodes/pininternal.png"
	  format="PNG"/>
      </imageobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/pinnodes/pininternal.eps"
	  format="EPS"/>
      </imageobject>
      <caption>
	<para>
	  Pinned nodes are shown in black.
	</para>
      </caption>
    </mediaobject>
  </figure>
  <figure id="Figure-pinsmooth">
    <title>Smoothing with Pinned Internal Boundary Nodes</title>
    <mediaobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/pinnodes/pinsmooth.png"
	  format="PNG"/>
      </imageobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/pinnodes/pinsmooth.eps"
	  format="EPS"/>
      </imageobject>
    </mediaobject>
  </figure>

